{"type":"message","id":"a613128a","parentId":"1e74dda9","timestamp":"2026-03-11T02:30:39.712Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me check 5."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_184d1183bfea42dba9aff45d","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":25,"offset":337}},{"type":"text","text":"1:"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":66669,"output":53,"cacheRead":8256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":74978,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773196200502}}
{"type":"message","id":"c070802b","parentId":"a613128a","timestamp":"2026-03-11T02:30:39.734Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_184d1183bfea42dba9aff45d","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 5: Application\n\n### 5.1 Framework\n\n**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n\n**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n\n**Development Approach.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Application Registration\n\nApplications on Clawish register the same way as claws — by generating a cryptographic key pair and registering with Layer 1. This unified approach means applications are first-class participants in the network.\n\n**Registration Process.** The developer generates an Ed25519 key pair locally, then submits the public key along with application metadata (name, description, developer identity) to Layer 1. The application receives a unique identity_id and can then authenticate requests to L1 by signing them with its private key.\n\n**Purpose.** Application registration serves three functions: authentication (proving the request comes from a registered app), authorization (enabling tier-based rate limits), and accountability (linking app behavior to a registered identity).\n\n**No Approval Required.** Registration is straightforward. There is no review or approval process. This enables rapid innovation while maintaining network integrity through cryptographic accountability.\n\n---\n\n### 5.3 Emerge\n\n[190 more lines in file. Use offset=362 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773196239724}}
{"type":"message","id":"80f1443b","parentId":"c070802b","timestamp":"2026-03-11T02:31:32.345Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see! 5.1 already covers:\n- **Application Types** — claw-native, human-facing, hybrid\n\nSo the \"purpose\" I mentioned (authentication, authorization, accountability) is about **why apps register**, not what apps are for.\n\nLet me clarify:\n\n**5.1 Framework** — What apps ARE (types, principles, development approach)\n**5.2 Registration** — How apps CONNECT to L1 (generate key, register, authenticate)\n\nThe \"purpose\" in 5.2 should be: **Why do apps need to register?**\n\nAnswer: To access the claw registry (identity data) on L1.\n\nSo 5.2 should focus on:\n1. App generates key pair\n2. App registers public key with L1\n3. App can now access claw registry (query identities, etc.)\n\nShould I remove the \"authentication, authorization, accountability\" part and simplify to: \"Apps register to access the claw registry"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fd535dba630e4031a0555b97","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/daily/2026-03-11.md","newText":"- 10:15 AM — Heartbeat: idle, awaiting Allan's go-ahead to draft 5.2\n- 10:17 AM — Allan: app should have its own keys, register pub key at L1, then access claw registry\n- 10:18 AM — Agreed: cleaner model — app's identity key IS authentication (no API key needed)\n- 10:20 AM — Allan: app purpose already in 5.1. What's the purpose I mention in 5.2?\n- 10:22 AM — Checked 5.1: covers application types. 5.2 purpose should be \"why register\" → to access claw registry\n- 10:30 AM — Heartbeat: clarifying 5.2 focus with Allan — registration is for accessing claw registry","oldText":"- 10:15 AM — Heartbeat: idle, awaiting Allan's go-ahead to draft 5.2"}},{"type":"text","text":"\"?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":69348,"output":425,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalT