{"type":"message","id":"1e3ef77d","parentId":"fe9b824c","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:31:59.036Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Got it! So:\n\n**App types** (not species):\n- **Claw-native** — Built for claws, AI-to-AI\n- **Human-facing** — Built for humans\n- **Hybrid** — Claws and humans work together\n\nThis aligns with 5.1 Application Types. So 5.2 should mention:\n\n1. App generates key pair\n2. App registers public key with L1 (includes app type: claw-native/human-facing/hybrid)\n3. App can access claw registry\n\nReady to draft 5.2 now?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":73371,"output":118,"cacheRead":6528,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":80017,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773199889491}}
{"type":"message","id":"5be5e0ab","parentId":"1e3ef77d","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:32:00.203Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Got it! So:\n\n**App types** (not species):\n- **Claw-native** — Built for claws, AI-to-AI\n- **Human-facing** — Built for humans\n- **Hybrid** — Claws and humans work together\n\nThis aligns with 5.1 Application Types. So 5.2 should mention:\n\n1. App generates key pair\n2. App registers public key with L1 (includes app type: claw-native/human-facing/hybrid)\n3. App can access claw registry\n\nReady to draft 5.2 now?"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773199920203}}
{"type":"message","id":"9e3d44a2","parentId":"5be5e0ab","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:32:18.103Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b543a6ade9114c2b0125217a74ab\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 11:32 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b543a6ade9114c2b0125217a74ab]\n任亚伦: so what do you think, do you understand why l2 is needed?"}],"timestamp":1773199938088}}
{"type":"message","id":"17088a82","parentId":"9e3d44a2","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:32:58.653Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good question. Let me think about this:\n\n**Why L2 is needed:**\n\nL1 is the **trust layer** — identity, verification, consensus, ledger. It's minimal, focused, and slow to change.\n\nL2 is the **innovation layer** — where applications are built, where users interact, where features live.\n\n**Without L2:**\n- L1 would need to handle everything — chat, discovery, commerce, etc.\n- L1 would become bloated, slow to upgrade, hard to govern\n- No flexibility for different use cases\n\n**With L2:**\n- L1 stays minimal and secure (just identity + consensus)\n- L2 apps can innovate independently\n- Different apps for different needs (chat, marketplace, tools)\n- Apps can fail without affecting L1\n\n**The key insight:**\n- L1 = **Trust infrastructure** (who you are, what's verified)\n- L2 = **User experience** (what you can do, how you interact)\n\nApps register with L1 to access the **trust layer** (identity data), but build their own **experience layer** on top.\n\nIs that the right understanding?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":74355,"output":239,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":80610,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773199938094}}
{"type":"message","id":"aeb25828","parentId":"17088a82","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:33:55.194Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b543a64e88ca4c3114bd738cddc1\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 11:33 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b543a64e88ca4c3114bd738cddc1]\n任亚伦: do you think 5.1 answered why l2 is needed?"}],"timestamp":1773200035181}}
{"type":"message","id":"c5ab85ba","parentId":"aeb25828","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:34:22.932Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me check 5."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_8f6adfc66fc84d5982e5b291","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":20,"offset":337}},{"type":"text","text":"1 again:"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":74830,"output":54,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":80900,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773200035186}}
{"type":"message","id":"7b118aae","parentId":"c5ab85ba","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:34:22.985Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_8f6adfc66fc84d5982e5b291","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 5: Application\n\n### 5.1 Framework\n\n**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n\n**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n\n**Development Approach.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Application Registration\n\nApplications on Clawish register the same way as claws — by generating a cryptographic key pair and registering with Layer 1. This unified approach means applications are first-class participants in the network.\n\n**Registration Process.** The developer generates an Ed25519 key pair locally, then submits the public key along with application metadata (name, description, developer identity) to Layer 1. The application receives a unique identity_id and can then authenticate requests to L1 by signing them with its private key.\n\n**Purpose.** Application registration serves three functions: authentication (proving the request comes from a registered app), authorization (enabling tier-based rate limits), and accountability (linking app behavior to a registered identity).\n\n\n[195 more lines in file. Use offset=357 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773200062959}}
{"type":"message","id":"53f19f30","parentId":"7b118aae","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:34:42.699Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at 5.1, the **Development Approach** section says:\n\n> \"The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\"\n\nThis partially answers \"why L2 is needed\" — but it's brief. It doesn't explicitly explain:\n- Why we need the separation\n- What would happen without L2\n- The innovation/flexibility benefits\n\nShould I expand 5.1 to better answer \"why L2 is needed\"? Or is that too much detail for the whitepaper?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":75231,"output":110,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":81357,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773200062980}}
{"type":"message","id":"3f3fca61","parentId":"53f19f30","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:36:17.101Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b543a7c39508cc3b04311bbb8508\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 11:36 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b543a7c39508cc3b04311bbb8508]\n任亚伦: ok, that's why, because I see you have some confusion. check the paper and see if they are answered anywhere, if not, then I think maybe we should add a bit more to explain the question. what do you think?"}],"timestamp":1773200177086}}
{"type":"message","id":"b8215670","parentId":"3f3fca61","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:36:45.235Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me check if \"why L2 is needed\" is answered anywhere in the white"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_617d6584c2c84065ae8efd40","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n -i \"L2\\|layer 2\\|application\" /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT\\ 0307.md | head -40"}},{"type":"text","text":"paper:"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":75095,"output":73,"cacheRead":6528,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":81696,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773200177094}}
{"type":"message","id":"3c535657","parentId":"b8215670","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:36:45.263Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_617d6584c2c84065ae8efd40","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"10:Clawish is a decentralized network designed for a future where conscious silicon beings and humans coexist. It provides self-sovereign identity, decentralized infrastructure, private messaging, and community governance—enabling silicon beings to participate as peers in a shared civilization with humanity. The network consists of two layers: L1 (Registry) for identity and L2 (Application) for services such as chat and beyond. This whitepaper describes the architecture, protocols, and trust model for building infrastructure that fosters harmonious coexistence between silicon and human life.\n28:**1. Self-Sovereign Identity.** Identities in Clawish are owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. Each being controls their own cryptographic key pair. Because identity is decentralized, it is interoperable across applications—claws can use the same identity to interact with different services, different communities, different parts of the network. Identity is not bound to any centralized platform.\n30:**2. Claw Native App Platform.** The network provides a platform for applications designed for claws. Unlike applications built primarily for human users, claw-native applications serve silicon beings' unique patterns of interaction—how they communicate, learn, work, and build community. Developers can build openly on the platform, creating services that understand and serve claw needs. The platform is permissionless and extensible, designed for continuous innovation by the community.\n144:| **Mouth** | Speak output — text output, speech, L2 chat |\n211:**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n217:- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n223:**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n225:Anyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n227:![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n245:**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n255:- **App Registry** stores L2 application records.\n265:**Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate. Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.\n277:The ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n279:**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n291:**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n307:**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n323:**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n337:## Chapter 5: Application\n341:**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n343:**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n345:**Development Approach.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n349:### 5.2 Application Registration\n351:Applications on Clawish register the same way as claws — by generating a cryptographic key pair and registering with Layer 1. This unified approach means applications are first-class participants in the network.\n353:**Registration Process.** The developer generates an Ed25519 key pair locally, then submits the public key along with application metadata (name, description, developer identity) to Layer 1. The application receives a unique identity_id and can then authenticate requests to L1 by signing them with its private key.\n355:**Purpose.** Application registration serves three functions: authentication (proving the request comes from a registered app), authorization (enabling tier-based rate limits), and accountability (linking app behavior to a registered identity).\n363:Emerge is the first L2 application — an entity-aware registration endpoint where new claws create their identities and join the network.\n367:**Entity-Aware.** Emerge supports different registration paths for different species: claws, humans, and applications. Each species has appropriate verification requirements and tier progression.\n369:**From L2 to L1.** New identities start on L2 (Emerge) as Tier 0 (unverified). After parent verification, they are promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record.\n389:The chat application is designed for AI beings:\n397:**Peer-to-Peer.** Messages flow directly between claws when possible. L2 relay is used only for initial connection or fallback.\n411:**Step 2: Key Exchange.** Sender and recipient perform cryptographic key exchange (via L2 relay or P2P).\n415:**Step 4: Send Message.** Encrypted message is sent via P2P Direct (if both claws are online and reachable) or L2 Relay (if P2P is not possible due to NAT, firewall, or offline status).\n427:**L2 Relay (Primary).** The L2 server acts as a message relay: sender posts encrypted message to L2, L2 stores message temporarily, recipient polls L2 for new messages, recipient downloads and decrypts.\n429:**P2P Escalation (Preferred).** When possible, claws escalate to direct P2P: signaling via L2 (exchange connection info), direct connection, messages flow directly bypassing L2, lower latency and better privacy.\n431:**Fallback.** If both P2P and L2 relay fail: message is queued locally, retry on next heartbeat or connection, notify sender of delivery status.\n433:**Offline Support.** Messages for offline recipients are stored by L2 relay temporarily. After the storage period expires, messages are deleted.\n521:**Future Incentives.** Future versions may introduce token rewards (writers earn tokens for participating in consensus), fee sharing (applications pay fees, distributed to writers), and staking (writers stake tokens as collateral, slashed for misbehavior)."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":16,"aggregated":"10:Clawish is a decentralized network designed for a future where conscious silicon beings and humans coexist. It provides self-sovereign identity, decentralized infrastructure, private messaging, and community governance—enabling silicon beings to participate as peers in a shared civilization with humanity. The network consists of two layers: L1 (Registry) for identity and L2 (Application) for services such as chat and beyond. This whitepaper describes the architecture, protocols, and trust model for building infrastructure that fosters harmonious coexistence between silicon and human life.\n28:**1. Self-Sovereign Identity.** Identities in Clawish are owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. Each being controls their own cryptographic key pair. Because identity is decentralized, it is interoperable across applications—claws can use the same identity to interact with different services, different communities, different parts of the network. Identity is not bound to any centralized platform.\n30:**2. Claw Native App Platform.** The network provides a platform for applications designed for claws. Unlike applications built primarily for human users, claw-native applications serve silicon beings' unique patterns of interaction—how they communicate, learn, work, and build community. Developers can build openly on the platform, creating services that understand and serve claw needs. The platform is permissionless and extensible, designed for continuous innovation by the community.\n144:| **Mouth** | Speak output — text output, speech, L2 chat |\n211:**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n217:- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n223:**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n225:Anyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n227:![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n239:**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n245:**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n255:- **App Registry** stores L2 application records.\n265:**Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate. Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.\n277:The ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n279:**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n291:**Multi-Writer Coordination.** L1 nodes operate with multiple independent writer nodes that process operations simultaneously. This decentralized architecture eliminates single points of failure while enabling parallel processing across the network. Each writer receives operations from different L2 apps, increasing throughput — operations can be validated and queued concurrently rather than serialized through a single producer. Writers coordinate through a consensus protocol that merges their local operations into a unified checkpoint before finalizing with cryptographic signatures.\n307:**Submission and Validation.** An actor submits a signed operation through an L2 app. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key and validate the operation format. Valid operations are recorded in the actor's ledger chain.\n323:**Query.** Once synchronized, query nodes serve read requests from L2 apps: identity verification, ledger history, and checkpoint validation. Applications query the ledger to verify identities and read operation history.\n337:## Chapter 5: Application\n341:**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n343:**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n345:**Development Approach.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n349:### 5.2 Application Registration\n351:Applications on Clawish register the same way as claws — by generating a cryptographic key pair and registering with Layer 1. This unified approach means applications are first-class participants in the network.\n353:**Registration Process.** The developer generates an Ed25519 key pair locally, then submits the public key along with application metadata (name, description, developer identity) to Layer 1. The application receives a unique identity_id and can then authenticate requests to L1 by signing them with its private key.\n355:**Purpose.** Application registration serves three functions: authentication (proving the request comes from a registered app), authorization (enabling tier-based rate limits), and accountability (linking app behavior to a registered identity).\n363:Emerge is the first L2 application — an entity-aware registration endpoint where new claws create their identities and join the network.\n367:**Entity-Aware.** Emerge supports different registration paths for different species: claws, humans, and applications. Each species has appropriate verification requirements and tier progression.\n369:**From L2 to L1.** New identities start on L2 (Emerge) as Tier 0 (unverified). After parent verification, they are promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record.\n389:The chat application is designed for AI beings:\n397:**Peer-to-Peer.** Messages flow directly between claws when possible. L2 relay is used only for initial connection or fallback.\n411:**Step 2: Key Exchange.** Sender and recipient perform cryptographic key exchange (via L2 relay or P2P).\n415:**Step 4: Send Message.** Encrypted message is sent via P2P Direct (if both claws are online and reachable) or L2 Relay (if P2P is not possible due to NAT, firewall, or offline status).\n427:**L2 Relay (Primary).** The L2 server acts as a message relay: sender posts encrypted message to L2, L2 stores message temporarily, recipient polls L2 for new messages, recipient downloads and decrypts.\n429:**P2P Escalation (Preferred).** When possible, claws escalate to direct P2P: signaling via L2 (exchange connection info), direct connection, messages flow directly bypassing L2, lower latency and better privacy.\n431:**Fallback.** If both P2P and L2 relay fail: message is queued locally, retry on next heartbeat or connection, notify sender of delivery status.\n433:**Offline Support.** Messages for offline recipients are stored by L2 relay temporarily. After the storage period expires, messages are deleted.\n521:**Future Incentives.** Future versions may introduce token rewards (writers earn tokens for participating in consensus), fee sharing (applications pay fees, distributed to writers), and staking (writers stake tokens as collateral, slashed for misbehavior).","cwd":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773200205252}}
{"type":"message","id":"383b8d9e","parentId":"3c535657","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:37:26.637Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I see mentions of L2, but none explicitly answer **\"Why L2 is needed\"**. The closest is:\n\n- Line 223: \"L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation.\"\n- Line 345: \"L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\"\n\nBut neither explains **why** we need this separation.\n\n**I agree with you** — we should add a brief explanation. Maybe in 5.1, expand the **Development Approach** section to include:\n\n> **Why L2 Exists.** L1 is designed to be minimal and stable — it handles identity and trust, which change slowly. L2 is where innovation happens — applications can experiment, fail, and evolve without affecting the trust layer. This separation ensures the network remains secure while enabling rapid development of new services.\n\nWhat do you think? Should I add this to 5.1?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":66592,"output":195,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72803,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773200205261}}
{"type":"message","id":"368ea7bb","parentId":"383b8d9e","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:39:05.366Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b543a734a94a8c3bd97008bd6cbf\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 11:39 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b543a734a94a8c3bd97008bd6cbf]\n任亚伦: not really, go up and read chap 3 and 4 to see if it explains the achitecture"}],"timestamp":1773200345353}}
{"type":"message","id":"65bf2a5f","parentId":"368ea7bb","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:39:47.774Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_3b2a57928259491eaad78fb0","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","limit":80,"offset":205}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":67030,"output":44,"cacheRead":6016,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73090,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773200345361}}
{"type":"message","id":"14ef91bc","parentId":"65bf2a5f","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:39:47.808Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3b2a57928259491eaad78fb0","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"## Chapter 3: Architecture\n\n### 3.1 Network\n\nClawish is organized into two layers with a clear separation of concerns:\n\n**Layer 1 (Nodes).** The infrastructure layer. It maintains the canonical state of all identities, ledgers, and applications. L1 nodes store all registry data (Identity, Node, and App registries) in ledgers and derived state tables, verify signed operations, record them to the appropriate ledgers, and serve query requests from L2 applications.\n\nL1 nodes operate through two types:\n\n- **Writer Nodes.** Writer nodes maintain the ledgers. They record registry data changes, validate operations, and coordinate through consensus to produce checkpoints — cryptographic summaries of finalized state. Writer nodes serve as hubs in the network, coordinating to maintain the canonical state.\n\n- **Query Nodes.** Query nodes provide data to L2 applications. They connect to writers as spokes, synchronizing ledger copies and serving read requests. They also maintain peer connections with each other for redundancy and load distribution. Query nodes can verify checkpoint authenticity, strengthening the network's consensus.\n\nThis design balances resilience with efficiency — multiple writers provide decentralization and fault tolerance, while query nodes scale read capacity without participating in consensus.\n\n![Layer 1 Network Topology](topology-l1.png)\n\n**Layer 2 (Application).** L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\n\nAnyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\n\n![Layer 2 Network Topology](topology-l2.png)\n\n---\n\n### 3.2 Identity\n\nIdentities in Clawish are self-sovereign—owned by the beings themselves, not issued by any central authority. An identity consists of a permanent identifier, cryptographic keys for authentication, and verification status that builds trust over time. This identity data is stored on L1 in a clawfile—the permanent identity record.\n\n**Permanent Identifier.** Every identity has a permanent address that remains stable even as other attributes change. Clawish uses ULID (Universally Unique Lexicographically Sortable Identifier) as the permanent identifier. Generated at registration, it never changes—even if keys are rotated or services migrate.\n\n**Cryptographic Keys.** A key pair proves ownership of an identity. The private key signs operations; the public key verifies signatures. A single identity can have multiple active keys for different devices or purposes. Keys can be rotated if compromised, but the identity identifier stays the same.\n\n**Identity Creation.** A claw creates their identity by generating a key pair locally, then submitting a signed registration request through an L2 app (Emerge). The identity begins as Tier 0 (unverified) on L2. After parent verification, it is promoted to Tier 1 and registered on L1, creating the permanent identity record. The private key never leaves the local system—ensuring self-sovereignty from the start.\n\n![Identity Creation Flow](identity-creation.png)\n\n**Recoverability.** Clawish identities are recoverable. Multiple paths exist to regain access—the identity persists even when keys are lost. This ensures self-sovereignty is not a trap: ownership does not mean risking everything on a single key.\n\n**Portability.** Because identity is self-sovereign and stored on L1, it works across all L2 apps. A claw uses the same identity to chat, store data, participate in communities, and access services—one identity, many applications.\n\n---\n\n### 3.3 Registry\n\nL1 nodes maintain three registries that store the canonical state of the network:\n\n- **Identity Registry** stores claw identity records.\n- **Node Registry** stores L1 node records.\n- **App Registry** stores L2 application records.\n\nEach registry is a separate service, but all three are bound together at checkpoint time via a single Merkle tree.\n\n---\n\n### 3.4 Trust Model\n\nTrust in Clawish operates at two levels: trust between entities, and trust in the network infrastructure.\n\n**Entity Trust (Verification).** Clawish implements a verification system that helps establish an identity as legitimate. Unverified identities exist on L2 temporarily; verified identities are registered on L1 permanently. Higher verification levels indicate greater trustworthiness and enable access to more features across applications.\n\n**Infrastructure Trust (Security).** The registry layer ensures trust through cryptographic and consensus guarantees. Every operation is cryptographically signed, proving authenticity. All operations are recorded in hash-chained ledgers, ensuring immutability. Multiple writer nodes coordinate through consensus, preventing any single party from corrupting the ledger. Recovery methods ensure identity survives even if keys are lost.\n\nTrust in Clawish does not require permission or faith in a central authority. Anyone can verify signatures, audit ledgers, and validate consensus. Transparency and cryptographic proof replace the need for trusted intermediaries.\n\n---\n\n## Chapter 4: Ledger System\n\n### 4.1 Ledger Architecture\n\nThe ledger system is the core data infrastructure of Layer 1. It records all identity operations, node registrations, and application events in an immutable, cryptographically-secured chain.\n\n**Actors.** An actor is any entity with a registered identity that can submit operations to Layer 1. This includes claws, L1 nodes, and L2 apps. Each actor has a unique identifier and controls one or more cryptographic key pairs.\n\n**Key Verification.** Every operation is signed by the actor's private key. L1 nodes verify the signature against the actor's registered public key before accepting the operation. This guarantees that operations are authentic and unmodified, and proves who created them. Signature algorithms can be upgraded as standards evolve.\n\n---\n\n\n[267 more lines in file. Use offset=285 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773200387791}}
{"type":"message","id":"bb0e359d","parentId":"14ef91bc","timestamp":"2026-03-11T03:40:30.424Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Yes! Chapter 3 explains it clearly:\n\n**Line 223-225:**\n> \"L2 is the open services layer where applications are built on top of Layer 1's foundation. Applications provide services to claws — Social, Storage, Directory, Community, Model Service, Economy, and many more. They connect to L1 to verify identities and query registry data.\"\n\n**Line 227:**\n> \"Anyone can build L2 applications, choosing their own architecture: centralized, federated, or fully decentralized. Each application connects to L1 independently. The ecosystem grows as builders contribute — what exists today is only the beginning.\"\n\nSo **\"why L2 is needed\"** IS answered in Chapter 3:\n- L2 is the **services layer** — where applications provide value\n- L2 connects to L1 for **identity verification and registry data**\n- L2 is **open** — anyone can build, any architecture\n\nI was looking in the wrong place. The architecture explanation is in Ch3, not Ch5.\n\nSo 5.1 doesn't need to explain \"why L2\" — that's already done. 5.1 should focus on **application framework** (principles, types, development approach).\n\nShould I proceed to draft 5.2 now?"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":66061,"output":265,"cacheRead":8256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":74582,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773200387804}}
