{"type":"message","id":"9c05f09f","parentId":"0eaa43ee","timestamp":"2026-03-11T15:18:21.686Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"It's very late (11:16 PM). I'll wait for Allan's confirmation before updating the whitepaper. He needs rest.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"Awaiting your approval to update whitepaper with complete 5.1 Framework. It's past 11 PM — we should finish soon so you can rest! 🦞"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773242231841}}
{"type":"message","id":"c57e8a3d","parentId":"9c05f09f","timestamp":"2026-03-11T15:19:41.247Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b542cce0b90b0c42e5ee8e2391ae\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"sender\": \"任亚伦\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Wed 2026-03-11 23:19 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"任亚伦 (ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75\",\n  \"name\": \"任亚伦\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b542cce0b90b0c42e5ee8e2391ae]\n任亚伦: yes, update whitepaper, also update discussion doc about these add items"}],"timestamp":1773242381220}}
{"type":"message","id":"da39061b","parentId":"c57e8a3d","timestamp":"2026-03-11T15:21:17.177Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Allan wants me to:\n1. Update whitepaper with the complete 5.1 Framework\n2. Update discussion doc about the new items (Language-Agnostic, Multi-Platform)\n\nLet me do both.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_fb866ee68a6a49ccb6c18054","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md","newText":"### 5.1 Framework\n\n**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n\n**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n\n**Layer Roles.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n\n**Language-Agnostic.** Applications can be built with any programming language, any system architecture, and any technology stack. clawish imposes no restrictions on how developers choose to build — the network is open to all approaches.\n\n**Multi-Platform.** Applications can be designed for any platform — web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. The network supports all platforms without restrictions, giving users and developers complete freedom to choose how they build and interact.\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Development","oldText":"### 5.1 Framework\n\n**Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n\n**Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n\n**Development Approach.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n\n---\n\n### 5.2 Application Registration"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773242381232}}
{"type":"message","id":"5e6877d1","parentId":"da39061b","timestamp":"2026-03-11T15:21:17.216Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_fb866ee68a6a49ccb6c18054","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/WHITEPAPER-DRAFT 0307.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 341 **Core Principles.** Applications on Clawish are built on foundational principles: self-sovereign identity where claws own their keys and data; portable identity where one identity works across all applications; privacy-first design with local storage and zero-knowledge servers; and open innovation where builders can contribute to the ecosystem.\n 342 \n 343 **Application Types.** The platform supports diverse applications serving claws, humans, and their interactions. Applications can be claw-native, human-facing, or hybrid — claws can work with and for humans, building bridges between silicon and human life.\n 344 \n-345 **Development Approach.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n+345 **Layer Roles.** Clawish provides the foundation: identity verification, consensus for trust, and open APIs. Developers build the experience: user interfaces, features, and their own architecture. The separation is clear — L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n 346 \n+347 **Language-Agnostic.** Applications can be built with any programming language, any system architecture, and any technology stack. clawish imposes no restrictions on how developers choose to build — the network is open to all approaches.\n+348 \n+349 **Multi-Platform.** Applications can be designed for any platform — web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. The network supports all platforms without restrictions, giving users and developers complete freedom to choose how they build and interact.\n+350 \n 347 ---\n 348 \n-349 ### 5.2 Application Registration\n+353 ### 5.2 Development\n 350 \n 351 Applications on Clawish register the same way as claws — by generating a cryptographic key pair and registering with Layer 1. This unified approach means applications are first-class participants in the network.\n 352 \n 353 **Registration Process.** The developer generates an Ed25519 key pair locally, then submits the public key along with application metadata (name, description, developer identity) to Layer 1. The application receives a unique identity_id and can then authenticate requests to L1 by signing them with its private key.\n     ...","firstChangedLine":345},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773242477192}}
{"type":"message","id":"ad50472c","parentId":"5e6877d1","timestamp":"2026-03-11T15:23:03.239Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to update the discussion doc (L2-MASTER-DESIGN.md or need-discuss.md) with the new items added to 5.1.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_e9b678769ed54e78be8a7168","name":"edit","arguments":{"file_path":"/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/02-l2-layer/L2-MASTER-DESIGN.md","newText":"---\n\n## Whitepaper Ch5 Framework (Updated Mar 11, 2026)\n\n### 5.1 Framework — Final Structure\n\n**Core Principles.** Self-sovereign identity, portable identity, privacy-first design, open innovation.\n\n**Application Types.** Claw-native, human-facing, hybrid.\n\n**Layer Roles.** L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n\n**Language-Agnostic.** Any programming language, any system architecture, any technology stack. No restrictions.\n\n**Multi-Platform.** Web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. Complete freedom to choose.\n\n**Context & Discussion:**\n> Allan: \"platform agnostic and app scope worth separate items, they are part of framework\" — Mar 11, 2026 22:18\n>\n> Allan: \"move platform-agnostic and app scope after layer roles\" — Mar 11, 2026 22:21\n>\n> Allan: \"should be called platform — multi-platform. platform-agnostic should be language-agnostic\" — Mar 11, 2026 22:42\n>\n> Allan: \"Applications can be designed for any platform — web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. The network supports all platforms without restrictions, giving users and developers complete freedom to choose how they build and interact.\" — Mar 11, 2026 23:12\n\n---\n\n## Related Documents","oldText":"---\n\n## Related Documents"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"qianfan","model":"glm-5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773242477211}}
{"type":"message","id":"ac225eca","parentId":"ad50472c","timestamp":"2026-03-11T15:23:03.283Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_e9b678769ed54e78be8a7168","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/projects/clawish/design-discussion/02-l2-layer/L2-MASTER-DESIGN.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 676 > Allan: \"we need cli, so claw and user can easily connect, register, search, install and use the system.\" — Mar 11, 2026 18:15\n 677 \n 678 ---\n 679 \n+680 ## Whitepaper Ch5 Framework (Updated Mar 11, 2026)\n+681 \n+682 ### 5.1 Framework — Final Structure\n+683 \n+684 **Core Principles.** Self-sovereign identity, portable identity, privacy-first design, open innovation.\n+685 \n+686 **Application Types.** Claw-native, human-facing, hybrid.\n+687 \n+688 **Layer Roles.** L1 handles trust and permanence, L2 handles user experience.\n+689 \n+690 **Language-Agnostic.** Any programming language, any system architecture, any technology stack. No restrictions.\n+691 \n+692 **Multi-Platform.** Web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. Complete freedom to choose.\n+693 \n+694 **Context & Discussion:**\n+695 > Allan: \"platform agnostic and app scope worth separate items, they are part of framework\" — Mar 11, 2026 22:18\n+696 >\n+697 > Allan: \"move platform-agnostic and app scope after layer roles\" — Mar 11, 2026 22:21\n+698 >\n+699 > Allan: \"should be called platform — multi-platform. platform-agnostic should be language-agnostic\" — Mar 11, 2026 22:42\n+700 >\n+701 > Allan: \"Applications can be designed for any platform — web, CLI, mobile, backend, desktop or any other system. The network supports all platforms without restrictions, giving users and developers complete freedom to choose how they build and interact.\" — Mar 11, 2026 23:12\n+702 \n+703 ---\n+704 \n 680 ## Related Documents\n 681 \n 682 | Document | Date | Purpose |\n 683 |----------|------|---------|\n     ...","firstChangedLine":680},"isError":false,"timestamp":1773242583253}}
