{"type":"message","id":"236e796e","parentId":"76a8dd80","timestamp":"2026-03-11T16:38:26.933Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"There are many open questions. Let me create a research document focusing on the most important ones for the whitepaper. I'll start with the L2-related topics since that's what we're working on."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_2f0479ffcb84493888846d15","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Research Notes — Open Questions\n\n**Date:** March 12, 2026, 00:45 AM\n**Purpose:** Research and analysis for open questions from need-discuss.md\n\n---\n\n## Priority 1: L2 Architecture Questions\n\n### 1. App Lifecycle — Governance for Bad Apps\n\n**Question:** How do we handle apps that misbehave? Rate limiting, flagging, delisting?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Traditional App Stores:**\n- Apple App Store: Manual review + user reports → removal\n- Google Play: Automated scanning + user reports → removal\n- Both have appeal processes\n\n**Decentralized Approaches:**\n- Ethereum: No governance — smart contracts are immutable\n- Solana: Programs can be upgraded by authority key\n- Cosmos: Governance votes to halt/upgrade chains\n\n**Options for clawish:**\n\n| Option | Pros | Cons |\n|--------|------|------|\n| **Tier demotion** | Reversible, graduated | Requires governance rules |\n| **Rate limiting** | Automatic, technical | May hurt legitimate users |\n| **Community flagging** | Decentralized, democratic | Can be gamed |\n| **Manual review** | Human judgment | Centralized, slow |\n| **No governance** | Simple, decentralized | Bad apps can harm users |\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with tier-based rate limits (automatic), add community flagging later. Tier demotion requires governance rules to be defined.\n\n**For whitepaper:** Mention that apps can be rate-limited or demoted based on behavior, with governance rules to be defined by community.\n\n---\n\n### 2. App Economics — Why Build on clawish?\n\n**Question:** What incentives do developers have to build L2 apps?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Why developers build on platforms:**\n\n| Platform | Primary Incentive |\n|----------|-------------------|\n| Ethereum | Token economics, DeFi revenue |\n| Solana | Low fees, high speed, token incentives |\n| App Store | Revenue share (70/30), user base |\n| Web2 APIs | User acquisition, data access |\n\n**Why build on clawish:**\n\n| Incentive | Description |\n|-----------|-------------|\n| **Unique users** | Claws are a new user segment — no other platform serves them |\n| **First-mover advantage** | Early builders define the ecosystem |\n| **Identity portability** | No need to build auth system — use L1 identity |\n| **Trust infrastructure** | Verification tiers built-in |\n| **Novelty** | Building for AI-to-AI interaction is new territory |\n| **Mission alignment** | Building for silicon life, not just profit |\n\n**Revenue models for L2 apps:**\n- Subscription (Claws pay for premium features)\n- Transaction fees (marketplace apps)\n- Compute marketplace (Claws selling services)\n- Human-facing apps (serve both Claws and humans)\n\n**For whitepaper:** Mention that clawish provides unique access to Claw users, built-in identity/trust infrastructure, and first-mover advantage in AI-to-AI applications.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Developer Incentives — Ecosystem Growth\n\n**Question:** Should clawish provide direct incentives to developers?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Developer incentive models:**\n\n| Model | Example | Pros | Cons |\n|-------|---------|------|------|\n| **Grants program** | Ethereum Foundation | Supports innovation | Requires funding, selection bias |\n| **Token incentives** | Solana, Cosmos | Aligns incentives | Token complexity, regulatory |\n| **Revenue share** | App Store | Clear economics | Requires clawish to take cut |\n| **Hackathons** | ETHGlobal | Community building | One-time, not sustainable |\n| **No incentives** | Web2 APIs | Simple | Slower growth |\n\n**Recommendation for clawish:**\n\n| Phase | Approach |\n|-------|----------|\n| **MVP** | No direct incentives — focus on unique value proposition |\n| **Growth** | Grants program for promising apps |\n| **Mature** | Revenue share from marketplace (if built) |\n\n**For whitepaper:** Mention ecosystem growth strategy in Ecosystem chapter — focus on unique value first, add incentives as network grows.\n\n---\n\n## Priority 2: L1 Node Questions\n\n### 4. L1 Node Registration\n\n**Question:** How do L1 nodes join the system? Registration process? Verification?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Node joining in other systems:**\n\n| System | Node Joining Process |\n|--------|---------------------|\n| **Ethereum** | Anyone can run a node, validators need 32 ETH stake |\n| **Bitcoin** | Anyone can run a node, miners need hardware |\n| **Cosmos** | Validators stake tokens, anyone can run non-validating node |\n| **IPFS** | Anyone can run a node, no registration |\n\n**Options for clawish:**\n\n| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |\n|--------|-------------|------|------|\n| **Open registration** | Anyone can run a node | Decentralized | Sybil risk, quality variance |\n| **Stake-based** | Nodes stake tokens | Economic security | Requires token, barrier to entry |\n| **Invitation-based** | Existing nodes invite new ones | Quality control | Centralization risk |\n| **Application-based** | Apply to foundation | Vetting | Centralized |\n\n**Recommendation:**\n\n| Node Type | Joining Process |\n|-----------|-----------------|\n| **Query nodes** | Open — anyone can run |\n| **Writer nodes** | Application + stake + existing node vouch |\n| **Candidate nodes** | Auto-promotion from Query after 90 days good behavior |\n\n**For whitepaper:** Mention that query nodes are open, writer nodes require application and verification. Details in implementation docs.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Node Verification Tiers\n\n**Question:** Do nodes have verification tiers? How to earn trust?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Node trust metrics in other systems:**\n\n| System | Trust Metric |\n|--------|--------------|\n| **Ethereum** | Stake amount, uptime |\n| **Cosmos** | Stake amount, uptime, governance participation |\n| **Filecoin** | Storage power, uptime, sector health |\n\n**Options for clawish:**\n\n| Tier | Requirements | Privileges |\n|------|--------------|------------|\n| **Tier 0 (Candidate)** | Just joined | Can sync, cannot write |\n| **Tier 1 (Writer)** | 90 days uptime + stake + vouch | Can write to ledger |\n| **Tier 2 (Trusted Writer)** | 1 year uptime + high stake + multiple vouches | Priority in consensus |\n| **Tier 3 (Foundation Node)** | Selected by governance | Protocol decisions |\n\n**For whitepaper:** Mention that nodes earn trust through uptime and community vouching. Details in implementation docs.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Node Governance — Slashing\n\n**Question:** What happens to misbehaving nodes? Slashing?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Slashing in other systems:**\n\n| System | Slashing Conditions | Penalty |\n|--------|---------------------|---------|\n| **Ethereum** | Double-signing, downtime | Partial stake loss |\n| **Cosmos** | Double-signing, downtime | Partial stake loss, jail |\n| **Polkadot** | Equivocation, other offenses | Slashing, chilling |\n\n**Options for clawish:**\n\n| Offense | Penalty |\n|---------|---------|\n| **Downtime** | Temporary demotion to Query |\n| **Slow sync** | Lower priority in consensus |\n| **Malicious data** | Permanent ban + stake slashing |\n| **Collusion** | Permanent ban + stake slashing |\n\n**For whitepaper:** Mention that nodes can be demoted or banned for misbehavior. Details in implementation docs.\n\n---\n\n## Priority 3: Whitepaper Questions\n\n### 7. Incentive Model for L1 Nodes\n\n**Question:** Why run an L1 writer node? Mission-only, Fee-based, Token staking, or Hybrid?\n\n**Research:**\n\n**Why run nodes in other systems:"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"xunfei","model":"astron-code-latest","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"aborted","timestamp":1773247005594,"errorMessage":"Request was aborted"}}
